    Scikit-Learn

    Scikit-Learn¶

    scikit-learn is an open-source machine learning library. It's build on top of NumPy (a numerical computing library) and Matplotlib (a data visualization library). The topic in this notebook will cover a typical work process of building a machine learning model, starting with preparing the data and finishing with the evaluation of the output results. The dataset used as a sample will be a hospital's heart disease record with 303 patient records.

    Picking an Estimator¶

    The fastest way to create a machine learning model is to use an estimator (of classifier or model) from Scikit-Learn (source). The following image is how an estimator could be selected based on the problem and the size of the data. Be noted that sometimes to get a satisfactory result we might peek around a bit and try out a few models.

    Since we know that the heart_disease.csv has 303 samples (or rows) and we want to predict whether a patient has heart disease. Using these parameters -

    • Number of samples: >50
    • Prediction: Categorical
    • Labeled Data: Yes

    and the cheat-sheet from scikit-learn above, we can conclude to use a Linear SVC.

    Additionally, in case the result doesn't satisfy the KNeighbors Classifier, SVC, and Ensemble Classifiers are still an option.

    Let's start with the Linear SVC (or Linear Support Vector Classifier) for more information about Linear SVC see scikit-learn or the arxiv.

    In [10]:
    Copied! 
    # Import LinearSVC from scikit-learn
from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC

# Set random seed for replicable
np.random.seed(42)

# Instantiate and fit the model
lsvc = LinearSVC(max_iter=10000000)
lsvc.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the model
lsvc.score(X_test, y_test)
    # Import LinearSVC from scikit-learn from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC # Set random seed for replicable np.random.seed(42) # Instantiate and fit the model lsvc = LinearSVC(max_iter=10000000) lsvc.fit(X_train, y_train) # Evaluate the model lsvc.score(X_test, y_test)
    Out[10]:
    0.8026315789473685

    We have successfully created a model that achieves a (mean) accuracy of 75%. Still, there is room for improvement. For example to increase the max_iter to a much higher number.

    This is worth taking note of is the error that pops up when finished running that line. This comment on this StackOverflow post has a quite detailed answer explaining the reason why the error message occurred. In short, the model hasn't been able to learn properly based on the condition we have set. We could fine-tune the hyperparameter of the model, for instance, increase the number of max_iter, and the error should disappear. As an example, when set max_iter=10,000,000 the error disappeared and also results gain a higher accuracy level to 80%.

    Our first try has a high accuracy level but that shouldn't be satisfied and encourage us to stop trying to improve the outcome. As suggested by the cheat sheet earlier, we still have a model to try. Let's continue with the KNeighborsClassifier and see has the result is.

    Evaluate Model¶

    Once a model has finishing training it is crucial to measure the trustworthiness of its predictions. Scikit-Learn has 3 different methods for evaluating a model.

    1. score(): is the fastest and easiest method to calculate the accuracy of the model
    2. Scoring parameters: using hyperparameter passing into a scoring function such as cross_val_score() or GridSearchCV()
    3. Problem specific methods: are specific stand-alone functions

    There are a lot of methods to evaluate the model's performance. We will only select a few in this notebook. The full list of measurements can be found here

    • Accuray: is the most common and easiest way to measure the accuracy of the model
    • Area under the ROC Curve: (ROC = Receiver Operating Characteristic) is the probability to predict the right outcome (more about this here)
    • Confusion Matrix: is a matrix that shows the summary of the prediction results (True Positive, False Positive, True Negative, False Negative)
    • Classification Report: a report of a collection of metrics, for instance - precision, recall, f1-score, etc.

    Accuracy¶

    Measuring accuracy is the default value for showing how accurate is the model

    • score(): is the fastest and easiest method to calculate the accuracy of the model
    • cross_val_score: a validation method that returns an array of accuracy by running the k-times

    score()

    Let's see what it looks like when using the score() function.

    In [13]:
    Copied! 
    # Use score()
rfc.score(X_test, y_test)
    # Use score() rfc.score(X_test, y_test)
    Out[13]:
    0.8157894736842105

    cross_val_score()

    cross_val_score is a method that takes a model (or estimator) that already be fit (or created) with its input data as a hyperparameter. Its actual name is k-fold cross-validation. The cross_val_score will run the model repeatedly for certain numbers (by default 5 times or cv=5)

    In [14]:
    Copied! 
    # Import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Evaluate model using cross_val_score
cross_val_score(rfc, X, y)
    # Import cross_val_score from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score # Evaluate model using cross_val_score cross_val_score(rfc, X, y)
    Out[14]:
    array([0.81967213, 0.86885246, 0.81967213, 0.8       , 0.75      ])

    ROC Curve¶

    ROC curve or Receiver Operating Characteristic curve is a graphical plot of the diagnostic ability of a binary classification system. In other words, it measures how accurate a positive prediction is (compare between True Positive and False Positive).

    First, we need to know that Positive/Negative stands for what the prediction is, while True/False states whether or not to prediction is correct.

    Let's look at an example of a covid-19 test. An ATK test is the same as a prediction of if we have the disease (Positive) or not (Negative). To confirm the ATK test (prediction) we would need another test in this case would be a PCR test to confirm. The outcome of the confirmation would show if we actually predicted right (True) or wrong (False).

    • True Positive: Positive - predict that we have covid, True - prediction was right
    • False Positive: Positive - predict that we have covid, False - prediction was wrong
    • True Negative: Negative - predict that we haven't covid, True - prediction was right
    • False Negative: Negative - predict that we haven't covid, False - prediction was wrong

    To calculate a ROC curve, we can use the roc_curve()

    In [15]:
    Copied! 
    # Import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve

# Make prediction with probabilities
y_probs = rfc.predict_proba(X_test)

# Keep probabilty and positive class only
y_probs = y_probs[:, 1]

# calculate fpr, tpr and threshold
fpr, tpr, threshold = roc_curve(y_test, y_probs)
    # Import roc_curve from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve # Make prediction with probabilities y_probs = rfc.predict_proba(X_test) # Keep probabilty and positive class only y_probs = y_probs[:, 1] # calculate fpr, tpr and threshold fpr, tpr, threshold = roc_curve(y_test, y_probs)

    The roc_curve() function will return the value of true-positive (tpr) and false-positive (fpr) that we needed to post a ROC curve.

    Now that we have calculated all the necessary values, let's plot the roc_curve. To keep everything nice and clean we will create a plot function.

    In [18]:
    Copied! 
    # Create plot function
def plot_roc_curve(fpr, tpr):
  # Plot ROC curve
  plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color="brown", label='ROC')
  # Plot base line (guess line)
  plt.plot([0, 1],[0, 1], color='darkblue', linestyle='--',label='Guess')
  # Customize plot
  plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
  plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
  plt.title('ROC Curve')
  plt.legend
  plt.show()
    # Create plot function def plot_roc_curve(fpr, tpr): # Plot ROC curve plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color="brown", label='ROC') # Plot base line (guess line) plt.plot([0, 1],[0, 1], color='darkblue', linestyle='--',label='Guess') # Customize plot plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate') plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate') plt.title('ROC Curve') plt.legend plt.show()
    In [19]:
    Copied! 
    # Run the plot function
plot_roc_curve(fpr, tpr)
    # Run the plot function plot_roc_curve(fpr, tpr)

    As mentioned, the ROC curve indicates the accuracy of a positive prediction. In an ideal state, the number of True Positive will be 1.0, which is very unlikely.

    Confusion Metrix¶

    A confusion matrix, also known as an error matrix, is a specific table that visualizes the performance of an algorithm. In other words, it shows the performance of the prediction of the trained machine learning model.

    Let's repeat the possible outcomes of a confusion matrix once again

    • True Positive: is an outcome where the model correctly predicts the positive class
    • False Positive: is an outcome where the model incorrectly predicts the positive class
    • True Negative: is an outcome where the model correctly predicts the negative class
    • False Negative: is an outcome where the model incorrectly predicts the negative class

    In Scikit-Learn we can easily calculate a confusion matrix by using the confusion_matrix() function

    In [20]:
    Copied! 
    from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

y_preds = rfc.predict(X_test)

confusion_matrix(y_test, y_preds)
    from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix y_preds = rfc.predict(X_test) confusion_matrix(y_test, y_preds)
    Out[20]:
    array([[28,  5],
       [ 9, 34]])

    We can easily plot a confusion matrix by using pandas.

    In [21]:
    Copied! 
    pd.crosstab(y_test, 
            y_preds, 
            rownames=["Actual Label"], 
            colnames=["Predicted Label"])
    pd.crosstab(y_test, y_preds, rownames=["Actual Label"], colnames=["Predicted Label"])
    Out[21]:
    Predicted Label 0 1
    Actual Label
    0 28 5
    1 9 34

    Furthermore, Scikit-Learn has also function(s) to plot a confusion matrix

    • from_estimator(): will plot a confusion matrix by taking the entire dataset and running it with the estimator that was previously created
    • from_predictions(): will plot a confusion matrix by comparing the prediction result and the test dataset result
    In [22]:
    Copied! 
    from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay

# Plot confusion matrix from the entire dataset
ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_estimator(estimator=rfc, X=X, y=y);
    from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay # Plot confusion matrix from the entire dataset ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_estimator(estimator=rfc, X=X, y=y);
    In [23]:
    Copied! 
    # Plot confusion matrix from predictions
ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_true=y_test, 
                                        y_pred=y_preds);
    # Plot confusion matrix from predictions ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_true=y_test, y_pred=y_preds);

    Classification Report¶

    The classification report is a collection of metrics. We can call a classification report by using the function classification_report() by passing a test value and prediction value. A collection report will include;

    • precision: is the ability to correctly predict positive outcomes. The mathematical equation is tp / (tp + fp).
    • recall: is the ability to correctly predict a positive outcome from all of the correct outcomes. The mathematical equation is tp / (tp + fn).
    • f1-score: is the measurement of the model's accuracy by calculating the precision and the recall of the model. Mathematical equation is tp / (tp + (FP + fn)/2).
    • support: is the number of samples that each metric was calculated on
    • accuracy: the accuracy of the model
    • macro avg: stands for macro average, which is the average precision, recall, and f1-score between classes. Be noted that this metric doesn't take class imbalance into account. This means that if one has more samples it will have a higher impact on the overall average value.
    • weighted avg: stands for a weighted average, which is the weighted average precision, recall, and f1-score between classes. It takes the samples size of each class into account which indicates a higher balance as the macro avg.
    In [24]:
    Copied! 
    from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

print(classification_report(y_test, y_preds))
    from sklearn.metrics import classification_report print(classification_report(y_test, y_preds))
                  precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.76      0.85      0.80        33
           1       0.87      0.79      0.83        43

    accuracy                           0.82        76
   macro avg       0.81      0.82      0.81        76
weighted avg       0.82      0.82      0.82        76

    For comparison purposes, we will look at an extreme case of 10,000 samples where a model predicts true positive 9,999 cases and has only 1 false positive prediction.

    In [25]:
    Copied! 
    # Where precision and recall become valuable
disease_true = np.zeros(10000)
disease_true[0] = 1 # only one case

disease_preds = np.zeros(10000) # every prediction is 0

pd.DataFrame(classification_report(disease_true, 
                                   disease_preds, 
                                   output_dict=True,
                                   zero_division=0))
    # Where precision and recall become valuable disease_true = np.zeros(10000) disease_true[0] = 1 # only one case disease_preds = np.zeros(10000) # every prediction is 0 pd.DataFrame(classification_report(disease_true, disease_preds, output_dict=True, zero_division=0))
    Out[25]:
    0.0 1.0 accuracy macro avg weighted avg
    precision 0.99990 0.0 0.9999 0.499950 0.99980
    recall 1.00000 0.0 0.9999 0.500000 0.99990
    f1-score 0.99995 0.0 0.9999 0.499975 0.99985
    support 9999.00000 1.0 0.9999 10000.000000 10000.00000

    As we can see that the model has a 99.99% accuracy. But is the model useful?

    When looking at the weighted avg we can see that the data is heavily biased and imbalance. So, next, we need to look at the precision and recall values. Both numbers are extremely high which is a good sign that the model has learned the data quite well. Although the model has shown a lot of positive signs we need to further explore the model to understand it more, such as are there data leaks, etc.

    Improving the Model¶

    Generally, the first model that we created often be the baseline or the reference model. Most often we will improve upon it. In this section, we will try to improve our results from the first created baseline model.

    From the base result, we can categorize the improvements methods into two groups.

    1. From the data perspective

      • Collecting more data: can we collect more data? The more data we have the more likely the model result will be improved.
      • Improve the data quality: for instance, better image quality, filling missing data.

    2. From the model perspective

      • Use better model: by using pre-trained models that have better results. We can use the cheat sheet above to look for a better model.
      • Improve the model: can we improve or fine-tune the existing model? Can we use better hyperparameters?

    In this notebook, it is difficult to improve the results from the data perspective.

    Until now we have tried to improve the results from the model perspective by changing the model and changing the hyperparameters.

    What we will do in this section is

    1. Re-preparing the data
    2. Create an evaluation function
    3. Create a base model using the LinearSVC and evaluate its result
    4. Improve the base model by adjusting a hyperparameter
    5. Change the model to RandomForestClassifier()
    6. Improve the model in 5 by changing a hyperparameter
    7. Use RandomizedSearchCV() on the model in 6
    8. Use GridSearchCV() on the model in 6
    9. Compare all models

    Re-preparing the data¶

    Previously the dataset has been split into 2 sets, training set, and testing set. Instead, we will use 3 sets where the additional set will be used to validate the model. The portion of the dataset will be

    • train set: 75%
    • test set: 15%
    • validation set: 15
    In [26]:
    Copied! 
    # Prepare data
np.random.seed(42)

# Shuffle the data
heart_disease = heart_disease.sample(frac=1)

# Split into X & y
X = heart_disease.drop("target", axis=1)
y = heart_disease["target"]

# Set split ratio
train_split = round(0.7 * len(heart_disease)) # 70% of data
valid_split = round(train_split + 0.15 * len(heart_disease)) # 15% of data

# Split the data into train, validation & test sets
X_train, y_train = X[:train_split], y[:train_split]
X_valid, y_valid = X[train_split:valid_split], y[train_split:valid_split]
X_test, y_test = X[valid_split:], y[valid_split:]
    # Prepare data np.random.seed(42) # Shuffle the data heart_disease = heart_disease.sample(frac=1) # Split into X & y X = heart_disease.drop("target", axis=1) y = heart_disease["target"] # Set split ratio train_split = round(0.7 * len(heart_disease)) # 70% of data valid_split = round(train_split + 0.15 * len(heart_disease)) # 15% of data # Split the data into train, validation & test sets X_train, y_train = X[:train_split], y[:train_split] X_valid, y_valid = X[train_split:valid_split], y[train_split:valid_split] X_test, y_test = X[valid_split:], y[valid_split:]

    Create an evaluation function¶

    The evaluation function will be used to calculate and visualize the results matrix.

    In [27]:
    Copied! 
    # Import dependencies
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

# Create evaluation function
def evaluate_predictions(y_true, y_preds):
  # Calculate results
  accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_preds)
  precision = precision_score(y_true, y_preds)
  recall = recall_score(y_true, y_preds)
  f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_preds)
  # Create results metric
  metric_list = {
      'accuracy': round(accuracy, 2),
      'precision': round(precision, 2),
      'recall': round(recall, 2),
      'f1': round(f1, 2)
  }
  # Print results
  print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%')
  print(f'Precision: {precision * 100:.2f}%')
  print(f'Recall: {recall * 100:.2f}%')
  print(f'F1 score: {f1 * 100:.2f}%')

  return metric_list
    # Import dependencies from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score # Create evaluation function def evaluate_predictions(y_true, y_preds): # Calculate results accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_preds) precision = precision_score(y_true, y_preds) recall = recall_score(y_true, y_preds) f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_preds) # Create results metric metric_list = { 'accuracy': round(accuracy, 2), 'precision': round(precision, 2), 'recall': round(recall, 2), 'f1': round(f1, 2) } # Print results print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%') print(f'Precision: {precision * 100:.2f}%') print(f'Recall: {recall * 100:.2f}%') print(f'F1 score: {f1 * 100:.2f}%') return metric_list

    RandomizedSearchCV¶

    We can keep changing the hyperparameters until we are satisfied with the result. But isn't there a better way?

    Yes, there is.

    RandomizedSearchCV() allows to randomly search through different hyperparameters to see which result works best. It is also the one that works.

    In [32]:
    Copied! 
    # Set hyperparamter grid
grid_1 = {"n_estimators": [10, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 1200],
          "max_depth": [None, 5, 10, 20, 30],
          "max_features": ["auto", "sqrt"],
          "min_samples_split": [2, 4, 6],
          "min_samples_leaf": [1, 2, 4]}
    # Set hyperparamter grid grid_1 = {"n_estimators": [10, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 1200], "max_depth": [None, 5, 10, 20, 30], "max_features": ["auto", "sqrt"], "min_samples_split": [2, 4, 6], "min_samples_leaf": [1, 2, 4]}

    The maximum models that RandomSearchCV() can possibly run would be 6x5x2x3x3 = 540 models. However, we can cap the models that it will test with the parameter n_iter.

    In [33]:
    Copied! 
    from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

np.random.seed(42)

rfc_3 = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=-1)

# Setup RandomizedSearchCV
rs_rfc = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rfc_3,
                            param_distributions=grid_1,
                            n_iter=20, # try 20 models total
                            cv=5, # 5-fold cross-validation
                            verbose=0) # print out results

# Fit the RandomizedSearchCV version of clf
rs_rfc.fit(X_train, y_train);

    # Another hyperparameter grid grid_2 = {'n_estimators': [1200, 1500, 2000], 'max_depth': [None, 5, 10], 'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt'], 'min_samples_split': [4, 6], 'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2]}

    From the grid above, GridSearchCV() will test all possible combination which is 3x3x2x2x2 = 72 models. We also can set the cross-validation parameter cv to split the data into k different scenarios, as we have done earlier.

    Let's briefly see what the graph tells us.

    • Accuracy: Improved Base Model and the GridSearchCV Model has the best accuracy
    • Precision: indicates how well it predicts the positive outcomes which the GridSearchCV Model performed best.
    • Recall: indicates how much positive outcomes are among all the correct outcomes.
    • F1-Score: shows the accuracy of the models by using precision and recall. The best performing models are Improved Base Model and GridSearchCV

    Overall the GridSearchCV performed best.

    Save and Load Model¶

    There are two possible ways to save a trained model from Scikit-Learn with either Pickle or JobLib. In this notebook, we won't do into details of those two libraries. For more information visit pickle or joblib.

    The question might be which one we should use. According to scikit-learn it is recommended to use JobLib because of its efficiency and ability to handle large arrays.

    However, let's try out both.

    Pickle¶

    The function dump() will save a preferred model by passing the model as a parameter and inserting another function open() as a parameter to save it. In the open() function we will pass the saving path or name included a wb sting (write binary) for saving the model.

    In [41]:
    Copied! 
    import pickle

# Save an existing model to file
pickle.dump(gs_rfc, open("gs_random_forest_model.pkl", "wb"))
    import pickle # Save an existing model to file pickle.dump(gs_rfc, open("gs_random_forest_model.pkl", "wb"))

    For loading a model, we will use the load() function with open() as a parameter function. In open() we will pass the model name and a string rb (read binary) for reading the model

    In [42]:
    Copied! 
    # Load a saved model
loaded_pickle_model = pickle.load(open("gs_random_forest_model.pkl", "rb"))
    # Load a saved model loaded_pickle_model = pickle.load(open("gs_random_forest_model.pkl", "rb"))

    Once successfully loaded the model, we can normally use the model as before.

    In [43]:
    Copied! 
    # Make predictions and evaluate the loaded model
pickle_y_preds = loaded_pickle_model.predict(X_test)
e = evaluate_predictions(y_test, pickle_y_preds)
    # Make predictions and evaluate the loaded model pickle_y_preds = loaded_pickle_model.predict(X_test) e = evaluate_predictions(y_test, pickle_y_preds)
    Accuracy: 84.78%
Precision: 87.50%
Recall: 84.00%
F1 score: 85.71%

    JobLib¶

    To save a model using JobLib, we use dump() function by passing the model and another parameter filename as the name or path for saving the project.

    In [44]:
    Copied! 
    from joblib import dump, load

# Save a model to file
dump(gs_rfc, filename="gs_random_forest_model_2.joblib")
    from joblib import dump, load # Save a model to file dump(gs_rfc, filename="gs_random_forest_model_2.joblib")
    Out[44]:
    ['gs_random_forest_model_2.joblib']

    To load a model we will simply use the load() function and pass a parameter filename with the model path and name with it.

    In [45]:
    Copied! 
    # Import a saved joblib model
loaded_joblib_model = load(filename="gs_random_forest_model_2.joblib")
    # Import a saved joblib model loaded_joblib_model = load(filename="gs_random_forest_model_2.joblib")

    Once successfully loaded the model, we can normally use the model as before.

    In [46]:
    Copied! 
    # Make and evaluate joblib predictions

e = evaluate_predictions(y_test, joblib_y_preds)
    # Make and evaluate joblib predictions joblib_y_preds = loaded_joblib_model.predict(X_test) e = evaluate_predictions(y_test, joblib_y_preds)
    Accuracy: 84.78%
Precision: 87.50%
Recall: 84.00%
F1 score: 85.71%

    As we can see, performance wise there is no difference in the results. It's is up to you to choose which method to use.
